{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"41164c20-994f-417b-8457-45e2613524d0","content":"Here are the **three MSBuild evaluation performance issues** found in this project:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Expensive recursive wildcard glob (line 9, `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` forces MSBuild to walk the **entire directory tree** during evaluation. This gets worse as the repo grows. Prefer narrow, targeted globs (e.g., `**\\*.txt`) or explicit file lists.\n\n### 2. File I/O via property function during evaluation (line 13, `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nCalling `System.IO.File.ReadAllText` performs **synchronous disk I/O at evaluation time**, blocking the evaluator. The `build-notes.txt` file itself confirms this is intentional but costly. Move this to a target that runs at build time instead.\n\n### 3. Deeply chained import hierarchy (`imports/`)\n```\ncsproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach nested `<Import>` adds evaluation overhead. Three levels is manageable, but this pattern scales poorly—flatten when possible or use `Directory.Build.props` to avoid the chain.\n\n---\n\n**Biggest wins:** Fix #1 (wildcard glob) and #2 (file read) first—they have the most direct evaluation cost. The import chain (#3) is a maintainability concern that becomes a real perf issue as the chain grows.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"100176b9-569e-4dd0-8834-01eb6a8967cd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a full picture of the project. Let me analyze the MSBuild evaluation performance issues.\n\nIssues I can identify:\n\n1. **Deeply nested imports chain**: `level1.props` → `level2.props` → `level3.props` — a 3-level import chain. Each import adds evaluation overhead. While 3 levels isn't catastrophic, it's a pattern that can grow.\n\n2. **Recursive wildcard glob**: `**\\*.*` in `AdditionalFiles` — this is a very expensive glob that traverses the entire directory tree. The `**` pattern forces MSBuild to enumerate every file in every subdirectory.\n   \n3. **Synchronous file I/O during evaluation**: There's a property function that reads from disk during project evaluation, which blocks the entire process and adds significant overhead.\n\nThese are the main performance bottlenecks I'm seeing.","outputTokens":612},"id":"4b57685c-a336-483c-942a-023f01ebc0a8","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:09:18.424Z","parentId":"34210be5-4175-41d1-a106-dc9f0a233366"}
